text: Well, I was looking forward to this, but now I'll be boycotting it instead. I found out that this film is yet another victim of the Hollywood hate machine and its desire to rewrite and omit history. In this case THEY HAVE MADE SURE TO OMIT THE PLANTING OF THE AMERICAN FLAG ON THE MOON!   The Telegraph reports that Canadian actor Ryan Gosling said that the American moon landing ‚Äútranscended countries and borders,‚Äù and that instead of being an American achievement, it was a ‚Äúhuman achievement.‚Äù Globalist propaganda garbage. It was an American achievement which happened during the Cold War and succeeded in the iconic moment of planting the American flag on the moon, with America being the only country so far to this day to actually achieve manned landings there. It was a human achievement, in a race between the U.S. and the Soviet Union at the time. Trying to avoid portraying such a historical moment just comes off as more Hollywood smothering of anything involving American patriotism.  And the Moral Panic by the pearl clutchers of our time continues... Keep your PC safe spaces to yourselves.  B O Y C O T T

text: I hope they do justice to Apollo 8. The moon landing was awesome, but Apollo 8 was literally the first time anyone had ever left orbit, orbited the moon, and successfully utilized the Saturn V. Not to mention, NASA went from having nothing, no flight plan, no computer programs, no crew, no mathematical calculations needed for such a journey, no LEM, which they would need to use as a back up engine incase the main one failed, and a rocket that had failed its last test, to successfully reaching three new milestones in spaceflight history in one mission, on their first try, and after only 4 months of practice and preparation (normally they prepped for 12 - 16 months). That is a badass story.

text: While apollo 11 is an amazing triumph in human history, i do not consider it the most interesting mission. Apollo 8 is astoundingly fascinating. While the first lunar landing mission gets most of the press,  Apollo 8 was the first time man travelled away from the earth, escaped gravity, and traveled  to another world in deep space. The risks were higher than any other mission. The saturn V had only ever been all-up tested twice before, and the last test was a partial failure. They went to the moon on a rocket with only two tests flight previously and none of those test flights included TLI (trans lunar injection) or going to the moon. The command module only flew once before in apollo 7. And when they got to the moon, they fired their service module engine and parked themselves in lunar orbit. And to make matters more perilous, they didn't take a lunar module. Had the same thing that happened to apollo 13, happened to apollo 8; the crew would've died. There was no lifeboat on apollo 8. All the procedures and navigation knowledge gained was a major boost to the program. It solved so many unknowns. If not for apollo 8, apollo 11 might not have happened until 1970. July of 69 was cutting it close.

text: Yes, that looks good. Neil was once characterised by a TV interviewer as "an easy man to talk to but a difficult man to know." His colleagues liked him and respected him even though they all wanted that First Man On The Moon slot. One of the reasons NASA bosses gave it to Neil was the fact he really didn't. "The most Neil ever wanted to be known as was as the first 'pilot' to land on the moon," as one of them said. (Unlike Buzz who pissed them all off with persistent annoying campaigning to be the first to get out and walk there.)  I'm glad to see 2 emergency situations show up in the trailer because they demonstrate the ice water in his veins: his Gemini mission when a thruster kept on firing, sending them tumbling end over end at an ever-accelerating rate, whereupon Neil fired the retros to send them into re-entry early which he hoped would fix the problem- and it did.  The other example was his crash of The Flying Bedstead- meant to mimic the lunar module with a vertical jet engine yet in far more dangerous earthly wind and gravity. A sudden gust caught and threw it into a very bad angle he was unable to recover from, and he ejected just 2 seconds before it struck the ground and blew up. Even his colleagues marvelled afterwards that he simply reflected "yeah, that's a tricky machine" and returned to work at the office that afternoon.   He was a steely-eyed missile man par excellence. I can't help thinking, despite NASA denials, that they did choose Neil in particular to handle the first manned landing because he'd really proven his cool in the face of death, and more than once. He wasn't just the guy who happened to show up on mission 11 in the flight rotation.   It looks like Ryan Gosling's underplayed him nicely and that they haven't over-sentimentalized the thing, which is always a hazard. I like the grim and steely-eyed tone I've seen in this trailer, will hazard a guess that NASA didn't go in and sanitize the script, and shall definitely seek it out in IMAX.

text: 0:49    The movie gets this wrong.  Armstrong was not cocky, and did not have this much confidence in the success of Apollo 11, because there were too many variables and possible modes of failure.   He has said that he felt there was a 1/3 chance of a successful landing and return, a 1/3 chance of safe return but no landing, and a 1/3 chance the crew would die trying, likely he and Aldrin on the surface.  NASA's philosophy during the Apollo years was that "the man is the one thing that will not fail".   So while the Apollo crews were always acutely aware of the possibility of failure, they trained and worked and planned and drove themselves so that *they* would not be the component that failed.   These guys were not average, run of the mill pilots, or even run of the mill military pilots.  They would be at the absolute peak of the aviation profession with military experience, test pilot experience, engineering responsibilities, and advanced degrees.  They helped to design the machines they flew.   Even among these men, Armstrong had more experience than most, flying the tricky and dangerous LLTV.   He made the first landing through sheer determination and hard work and force of will.   He deserved to be first.

text: Great movie but there was something unexpected.  Like a typical Hollywood action flick there were these buildups, intense sequences, etc.  A powerful human story, and what they showed was historically accurate.  But unlike most action flicks the real life truth was far more intense and precarious than the movie could hope to portray.  They showed a small slice of Neil Armstrong's X-15 testing and astronaut experiences.  But they didn't show his years as a test pilot, flying off carriers in his 20's, his being shot down in Korea, or nearly being killed on various occasions.  The same goes for the rest of the these guys, and the endless smaller testing steps (Apollo), plus the staggering engineering challenges.  The truth is so much more amazing, more dangerous and more intense by orders of magnitude than this movie.  Real life trumps easily fiction here...and THAT is inspiring!

text: Saw it the other night & thought It was a really good movie.  But it's not a fast paced, wham-bam, extravaganza like Armageddon or even Apollo 13.   It's a quiet film & mostly dramatic with a few intense action scenes that are truly riveting.  But, overall, it's a serious drama.  So it's not for ppl who are impatient or immature.  And the fact that they didn't plant the flag didn't bother me because it wasn't necessary to the story & it also didn't  make it un-American or non-patriotic.  There is plenty of American symbolism & credit given in the film.  So if you're boycotting it, or on the fence, you need to try to let go of that & give it a chance.  If you don't, you'll not only be missing out on one of the finest films about the space program but also one of the best films of the year

And yet this conspiracy still persists with no evidence that would ever reach a level that's found in court.   Don't use your hatred of America or the  inefficiency of government programs to blind yourself to man's accomplishments, because you are not only denying human progress, but you hurting any kind of political development by associating small state movements with conspiracy theories. text: *One of the WORST movies I have seen regarding the Space Race.* It depicted Neil Armstrong as a very troubled depressed person who rarely knew how to handle anything in life without depression, withdrawing into a fantasy world and sadness. His home life was showed as a total failure with Armstrong too afraid to even talk to his kids before leaving for the Apollo 11 flight.  Armstrong is seen as lost, not knowing what to do with his life, very unfriendly, in his own little world and a person with a terrible bad attitude.  The scenes of the space crafts (especially the Gemini 8) are filmed as old rust buckets that are dirty, falling apart and poorly built. Case in point; many of the switches in the Gemini 8 cockpit were rusted, paint worn off surfaces, and sound effects for the Gemini 8 that sounded like a 100 year old tug boat about to fall apart.  A very poorly made ridiculous movie that seemed to be produced to belittle NASA and the U.S. Space Program as a broken down program run by idiots who hired an emotionally hurt and depressed test pilot, Neil Armstrong, for a mission that was carried out in piles of space junk.  The producers went out of their way to include scene after scene of Armstrong sitting in the dark, depressed, trying to figure life out, not having any clear goals in his life.  FOUR THUMBS DOWN! ...terrible movie!!

text: This movie is as uninteresting and uninspiring as you could possibly make about one of mankind's greatest achievements. The artsy attempt to make Neil Armstrong boring and jaded simply didn't work, and I wish I'd never seen this movie. How can anyone take something so spirited and profound as going to another world and make it seem as lame as an office cubicle in an earthquake? This shitty spin on Apollo 11 is a great disservice to an entire generation of young people who's first experience with this subject will be this horrible stoic movie. What a joyless dispiriting piece of shit.   The real world of space travel is a serious thing, but it's certainly not this humorless and bland. I didn't even learn anything new about the topics.  As someone who loves sci-fi and all modern space exploration,  I highly recommend skipping this soul crushing movie.

text: My heart breaks when I read the reviews for this movie on IMDB and other places. A movie about Mr. Neil Armstrong was always going to be hard but this film does him justice. Whilst I do feel very much for the movie patrons who were expecting something other than what this is, yes you would feel duped and I understand that. But in life you should have more than one gear - just sayin. This is closer to 2001 - A Space Odyssey rather than Apollo 13. To be in the shoes of the people surrounded by extremes in both expectation and fallible technology, they overcame insurmountable odds to achieve something that has been dreamt about since we could first look up at the night sky - so basically forever. This is a film of the sacrifices made by the men, women and citizens of a nation who were responsible for getting all of us there. If you cannot or do not think you can be a witness to the majesty that underlies these events then please go and watch something else. FYI - I am not American but am capable of giving credit where it is due. Thanks for reading this far btw.

text: Twelve people have walked on the Moon, starting with Neil Armstrong and ending with Gene Cernan. All crewed lunar landings took place between July 1969 and December 1972 as part of the Apollo program. Alan Shepard was the oldest person to walk on the Moon, at age 47 years and 80 days.  There are six U.S. flags on the moon planted by the Apollo astronauts (Apollo 11, 12, 14, 15, 16, and 17).  The first footprints put on the moon will probably be there a long, long time ‚Äî maybe almost as long as the moon itself lasts. Unlike on Earth, there is no erosion by wind or water on the moon because it has no atmosphere and all the water on the surface is frozen as ice.  Vice President Mike Pence has promised that we will see US astronauts on the moon by 2024 (including the first women to ever touch the lunar surface), in a program called Artemis.
